0 Singapore Grand Prix|SIN]]<br>\n| style=\"background:#\"|[[2020 Russian Grand Prix|RUS]]<br>\n| style=\"background:#\"|[[2020 Japanese Grand Prix|JPN]]<br>\n| style=\"background:#\"|[[2020 United States Grand Prix|USA]]<br>\n| style=\"background:#\"|[[2020 Mexico City Grand Prix|MEX]]<br>\n| style=\"background:#\"|[[2020 Brazilian Grand Prix|BRA]]<br>\n| style=\"background:#\"|[[2020 Abu Dhabi Grand Prix|ABU]]<br>\n| style=\"background:#\"|[[2020 Australian Grand Prix|AUS]]<sup>\u2021</sup><br>\n| style=\"background:#\"|[[2020 Bahrain Grand Prix|BHR]]<sup>\u2021</sup><br>\n| style=\"background:#\"|[[2020 Chinese Grand Prix|CHN]]<sup>\u2021</sup><br>\n| style=\"background:#\"|[[2020 Vietnamese Grand Prix|VIE]]<sup>\u2021</sup><br>\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|}\n;Notes\n{{smallsup|*}} Championship in progress.<br/>\n{{smallsup|\u2020}} Driver failed to finish the race, but was classified as they had completed over 90% of the winner's race distance.<br>\n{{smallsup|\u2021}} Multiple Grands Prix were postponed in response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 coronavirus outbreak]].\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Racing Point}}\n{{F1 cars 2020}}\n{{F1 cars 2021}}\n\n[[Category:Racing Point Formula One cars|RP20]]\n[[Category:2020 Formula One season cars]]\n\n{{F1-stub}}\n", "name_user": "5225C", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Racing_Point_RP20"}
{"title_page": "Clone Hero", "text_new": "{{short description|Indie rhythm video game}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| image = File:CloneHeroLogo.png\n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Linux]]\n| genre = [[Rhythm game]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n| released = March 2017\n}}\n\n'''''Clone Hero''''' is an [[Indie game|indie]] [[Rhythm game|rhythm]] [[video game]] created by a small team of developers led by a user under the pseudonym of \"Srylain The 2nd\", first released circa March 2017. The game is a [[Clone (computing)|clone]] of the ''[[Guitar Hero]]'' franchise, and as such, features nearly identical gameplay. The main draw of the game is its ability to play community-made songs, which has resulted in a large [[Fandom|fan community]] around the game.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n''Clone Hero'', by design, features nearly identical gameplay to ''Guitar Hero''. Specifically, the game is most similar to later entries in the series such as ''[[Guitar Hero World Tour|World Tour]]'' and ''[[Guitar Hero: Warriors of Rock|Warriors of Rock]]''. Gameplay involves pressing colored buttons on a [[guitar]]-shaped controller to play along to songs, although in ''Clone Hero'' these inputs can be mapped to a keyboard or any other input device. Players must hold specific buttons that line up with colored notes that appear on the screen on a \"highway\"; when the notes hit the bottom of the highway, the player must strum to hit the notes in time with the music. There is also an \"open strum\" note, represented with a purple bar, which requires the player to strum without pressing any other buttons. In addition to normal notes, there are \"HOPO\"s (\"[[Hammer-on|Hammer-ons]]\" and \"[[Pull-off|Pull-offs]]\") and \"tap notes\", which both do not require the player to strum them to hit them, with the difference between the two being that a string of HOPOs must begin with a strum, and the player must re-strum if they miss a note. Unlike the ''Guitar Hero'' series, by default there is no penalty for missing notes, aside from breaking a combo, making it impossible to fail a song. The game also contains a mode which emulates the gameplay of ''[[Guitar Hero Live]]'', which is notably different from other games in the series.\n\n=== Community-made charts ===\n''Clone Hero'' has the ability to play community-made songs, called \"charts\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-05-01-meet-the-community-reviving-classic-guitar-hero-gameplay-in-their-own-clone|title=The spirit of Guitar Hero lives on in a bizarre community-made clone|last=Stubbs|first=Mike|date=2018-05-01|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/guitar-heroes-never-die-they-just-start-playing-clone-1828254899|title=Guitar Heroes never die, they just start playing Clone Hero|last=Neilan|first=Dan|date=August 10, 2018|website=AV Club|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> However, unlike games in the ''Guitar Hero'' series, these songs do not need to be original compositions, and can instead be any audio file a member of the community wishes to turn into a playable chart. This allows for any song to be made playable in the game, but also leads to many non-musical audio files being turned into charts,<ref name=\":1\" /> as well as the creation of many intentionally impossible charts.<ref name=\":0\" /> The freedom offered by the game's system has also spawned many charts that are created as brutal challenges to other players, far beyond the difficulty of anything in the standard ''Guitar Hero'' series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/meet-the-streamer-making-guitar-hero-cool-again-one-insanely-hard-song-at-a-time/|title=Meet the streamer making Guitar Hero cool again, one insanely hard song at a time|last=Winkie|first=Luke|date=2018-07-24|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/insane-guitar-hero-performance-goes-viral-after-jaw-dropping-speedrun-1312256|title=Insane Guitar Hero performance goes viral after jaw-dropping \"speedrun\"|last=Bennett|first=Connor|date=January 13, 2020|website=Dexerto|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> While ''Clone Hero'' includes the main 4 difficulty modes seen in ''Guitar Hero'', the vast majority of charts are designed for Expert mode.\n\n== Reception ==\n''Clone Hero'', along with ''Guitar Hero'', was listed as one of ''Gamepur''<nowiki/>'s top 10 best rhythm games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamepur.com/features/10-best-rhythm-games|title=10 Best Rhythm Games|date=2020-01-22|website=Gamepur|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> ''Clone Hero'' has also made an appearance at [[Games Done Quick|Awesome Games Done Quick]] 2020.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/2020/01/11/undertale-sans-wild-agdq-video/|title=Undertale's Sans Appears in Wild AGDQ Video|last=Deschamps|first=Marc|date=January 13, 2020|website=Comicbook.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://clonehero.net/}}\n\n{{Guitar Hero series}}\n\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Guitar Hero]]\n[[Category:Guitar video games]]\n[[Category:Music video games]]\n[[Category:Musician video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:Software clones]]\n[[Category:2017 video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indie rhythm video game}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| image = File:CloneHeroLogo.png\n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], [[OS X]], [[Linux]]\n| genre = [[Rhythm game]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n| released = March 2017\n}}\n\n'''''Clone Hero''''' is an [[Indie game|indie]] [[Rhythm game|rhythm]] [[video game]] created by a small team of developers led by a user under the pseudonym of \"Srylain The 2nd\", first released circa March 2017. The game is a [[Clone (computing)|clone]] of the ''[[Guitar Hero]]'' franchise, and as such, features nearly identical gameplay. The main draw of the game is its ability to play community-made songs, which has resulted in a large [[Fandom|fan community]] around the game.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n''Clone Hero'', by design, features nearly identical gameplay to ''Guitar Hero''. Specifically, the game is most similar to later entries in the series such as ''[[Guitar Hero World Tour|World Tour]]'' and ''[[Guitar Hero: Warriors of Rock|Warriors of Rock]]''. Gameplay involves pressing colored buttons on a [[guitar]]-shaped controller to play along to songs, although in ''Clone Hero'' these inputs can be mapped to a keyboard or any other input device. Players must hold specific buttons that line up with colored notes that appear on the screen on a \"highway\"; when the notes hit the bottom of the highway, the player must strum to hit the notes in time with the music. There is also an \"open strum\" note, represented with a purple bar, which requires the player to strum without pressing any other buttons. In addition to normal notes, there are \"HOPO\"s (\"[[Hammer-on|Hammer-ons]]\" and \"[[Pull-off|Pull-offs]]\") and \"tap notes\", which both do not require the player to strum them to hit them, with the difference between the two being that a string of HOPOs must begin with a strum, and the player must re-strum if they miss a note. Unlike the ''Guitar Hero'' series, by default there is no penalty for missing notes, aside from breaking a combo, making it impossible to fail a song. The game also contains a mode which emulates the gameplay of ''[[Guitar Hero Live]]'', which is notably different from other games in the series.\n\n=== Community-made charts ===\n''Clone Hero'' has the ability to play community-made songs, called \"charts\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2018-05-01-meet-the-community-reviving-classic-guitar-hero-gameplay-in-their-own-clone|title=The spirit of Guitar Hero lives on in a bizarre community-made clone|last=Stubbs|first=Mike|date=2018-05-01|website=Eurogamer|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.avclub.com/guitar-heroes-never-die-they-just-start-playing-clone-1828254899|title=Guitar Heroes never die, they just start playing Clone Hero|last=Neilan|first=Dan|date=August 10, 2018|website=AV Club|language=en-us|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> However, unlike games in the ''Guitar Hero'' series, these songs do not need to be original compositions, and can instead be any audio file a member of the community wishes to turn into a playable chart. This allows for any song to be made playable in the game, but also leads to many non-musical audio files being turned into charts,<ref name=\":1\" /> as well as the creation of many intentionally impossible charts.<ref name=\":0\" /> The freedom offered by the game's system has also spawned many charts that are created as brutal challenges to other players, far beyond the difficulty of anything in the standard ''Guitar Hero'' series.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/meet-the-streamer-making-guitar-hero-cool-again-one-insanely-hard-song-at-a-time/|title=Meet the streamer making Guitar Hero cool again, one insanely hard song at a time|last=Winkie|first=Luke|date=2018-07-24|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dexerto.com/entertainment/insane-guitar-hero-performance-goes-viral-after-jaw-dropping-speedrun-1312256|title=Insane Guitar Hero performance goes viral after jaw-dropping \"speedrun\"|last=Bennett|first=Connor|date=January 13, 2020|website=Dexerto|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> While ''Clone Hero'' includes the main 4 difficulty modes seen in ''Guitar Hero'', the vast majority of charts are designed for Expert mode.\n\n== Reception ==\n''Clone Hero'', along with ''Guitar Hero'', was listed as one of ''Gamepur''<nowiki/>'s top 10 best rhythm games.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamepur.com/features/10-best-rhythm-games|title=10 Best Rhythm Games|date=2020-01-22|website=Gamepur|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> ''Clone Hero'' has also made an appearance at [[Games Done Quick|Awesome Games Done Quick]] 2020.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://comicbook.com/gaming/2020/01/11/undertale-sans-wild-agdq-video/|title=Undertale's Sans Appears in Wild AGDQ Video|last=Deschamps|first=Marc|date=January 13, 2020|website=Comicbook.com|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|https://clonehero.net/}}\n\n{{Guitar Hero series}}\n\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Guitar Hero]]\n[[Category:Guitar video games]]\n[[Category:Music video games]]\n[[Category:Musician video games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:Software clones]]\n", "name_user": "AntiGravityMaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clone_Hero"}
{"title_page": "Apple motion coprocessors", "text_new": "{{Infobox CPU\n| name           = Apple M-series coprocessors\n| image          = [[File:NXP LPC18A1.jpg|200px]]\n| caption        = The NXP LPC18A1, also known as the M7 motion coprocessor\n| produced-start = September 2013\n| produced-end   = present\n| slowest        = 150<ref name=\"NXP-docs\" >{{cite techreport |url=http://www.nxp.com/documents/leaflet/lpc18xx.pdf |title=NXP 150 MHz, 32-bit Cortex-M3 microcontrollers LPC1800 |number=9397 750 17002 |publisher=NXP Semiconductors |format=PDF |date=September 2010 |accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> | slow-unit = MHz\n| size-from      = 90&nbsp;nm<ref name=\"NXP-docs\"/>\n| arch           = [[ARMv7-M]]<ref name=\"NXP-docs\"/>\n| microarch      = [[Cortex-M3]]<ref name=\"NXP-docs\"/>\n| code           = M7: LPC18A1<ref name=\"Chipworks-M7\" /><br />M8: LPC18B1<ref name=\"ifixiph6p\"/>\n| numcores       = 1<ref name=\"NXP-docs\"/>\n| manuf1         = [[NXP Semiconductors]]<ref name=\"Chipworks-M7\" /><br/>[[TSMC]] (under contract)<br>[[Samsung]] (under contract)<br/>[[Apple Inc.]] (licensee)\n| designfirm     = [[NXP Semiconductors]]\n}}\nThe '''Apple M-series coprocessors''' are motion [[coprocessor]]s used by [[Apple Inc.]] in their mobile devices. First released in 2013, their function is to collect sensor data from integrated [[accelerometer]]s, [[gyroscope]]s and [[compass]]es and offload the collecting and processing of sensor data from the main [[central processing unit]] (CPU).\n\n{{As of|2017|05}}, the M-series coprocessors so far released have been the '''M7''' (codename ''Oscar''), the '''M8''', the '''M9''', the '''M10''', the '''M11,''' the '''M12,''' and the '''M13'''. The M7 was introduced in September 2013 with the [[iPhone 5S]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Estes |first=Adam Clark |url=https://gizmodo.com/how-apples-m7-chip-makes-the-iphone-5s-the-ultimate-tr-1286594287 |title=How Apple's M7 Chip Makes the iPhone 5S the Ultimate Tracking Device |publisher=Gizmodo |date=2013-09-10 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sumra |first=Husain |url=http://www.macrumors.com/2013/09/10/iphone-5s-includes-new-m7-motion-coprocessor-for-health-and-fitness-tracking/ |title=iPhone 5s Includes New 'M7' Motion Coprocessor for Health and Fitness Tracking |publisher=MacRumors |date=2013-09-10 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref> and the updated version, M8 was introduced in September 2014 with the [[iPhone 6]] and also processes data from the [[barometer]] that is included in the [[iPhone 6]] and [[iPad Air 2]].<ref name=\"iphone6-tech\">[https://www.apple.com/iphone-6/technology/ Apple - iPhone 6 - Technology]</ref><ref name=\"ipadair2-tech\">[https://www.apple.com/ipad-air-2/performance/ Apple - iPad Air 2 - Performance]</ref> September 2015 brought the M9 motion coprocessor embedded within the [[Apple A9|A9]] chip found in the [[iPhone 6S]], [[iPhone 6S Plus]], [[iPhone SE]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-se/specs/|title=iPhone SE - Technical Specifications|website=Apple|access-date=2016-06-14}}</ref> and within the [[Apple A9X|A9X]] chip found in the [[iPad Pro]].<ref name=\"iPhone_6S_press_release\">[https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2015/09/09Apple-Introduces-iPhone-6s-iPhone-6s-Plus.html Apple Introduces iPhone 6s & iPhone 6s Plus]</ref><ref name=\"ipadpro_tech_specs\">[https://www.apple.com/ipad-pro/specs/ iPad Pro - Apple]</ref> The [[iPhone 7]], [[iPad Pro]] 10.5-inch and 12.9-inch feature the M10 motion coprocessor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-7/specs/|title=iPhone 7 - Technical Specifications|website=Apple|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-08}}</ref>  Apple included the M11 in the [[iPhone 8]], 8 Plus and [[iPhone X]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-x/specs/|title=iPhone X - Technical Specifications|website=Apple|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-17}}</ref>. The most recent addition to the M-series processor line is the M13, which first appeared embedded into the A13 Bionic processor found in the iPhone 11, 11 Pro and 11 Pro Max.\n\nChip-works found that the M7 most likely is a [[NXP Semiconductors|NXP]] [[LPC1800]] based [[microcontroller]] called '''LPC18A1'''. It uses an [[ARM Cortex-M#Cortex-M3|ARM Cortex-M3]] core with a customised packaging and naming scheme indicating that it is for an Apple customized part.<ref name=\"Chipworks-M7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-iphone-5s/|title=Inside the iPhone 5s|first1=Jason|last1=Tanner|first2=Jim|last2=Morrison|first3=Dick|last3=James|first4=Ray|last4=Fontaine|first5=Phil|last5=Gamache|publisher=Chipworks|date=September 20, 2013|accessdate=September 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803201521/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-iphone-5s/|archive-date=August 3, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[iFixit]] have identified the\nM8 in the iPhone 6 to be an NXP device with a very similar name, the '''LPC18B1'''.<ref name=\"ifixiph6p\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/iPhone+6+Plus+Teardown/29206|publisher=iFixit|title=iPhone 6 Plus Teardown|accessdate=2014-09-20}}</ref><ref name=\"ifixiph6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/iPhone+6+Teardown/29213|publisher=iFixit|title=iPhone 6 Teardown|accessdate=2014-09-20}}</ref>\n\n== Usage ==\nThe Apple M7, M8, M9, M10, M11, M12 and M13 coprocessors collect, process, and store sensor data even if the device is asleep, and applications can retrieve data when the device is powered up again. This reduces power draw of the device and saves battery life.<ref name=\"AnandTech-iPhone5s-M7\">{{cite web |first=Anand |last=Lal Shimpi |url=http://anandtech.com/show/7335/the-iphone-5s-review/8 |title=The iPhone 5s Review: M7 Motion Coprocessor |publisher=AnandTech |date= 2013-09-17 |accessdate= 2013-09-18}}</ref> In addition to servicing the [[accelerometer]], [[gyroscope]], [[compass]], and in M8 and later coprocessors, [[barometer]], the M9 coprocessor can recognize [[Siri]] voice commands from the built in [[Microphone|microphones]] of the device.<ref name=\"Apple iPhone 6S Tech\">{{cite web |url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-6s/technology/ |title=iPhone 6s - Technology |publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] |date=September 8, 2015 |accessdate=September 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe M-series motion coprocessors are accessible to applications through the ''Core Motion'' [[Application programming interface|API]] introduced in [[iOS 7]], so they do, for example, allow [[fitness app]]s that track physical activity and access data from the M processors without constantly engaging the main application processor. They enable applications to be aware of what type of movement the user is experiencing, such as driving, walking, running, or sleeping.<ref>{{cite web|last=Martin |first=Mel |url=http://www.tuaw.com/2013/09/12/the-iphones-m7-motion-coprocessor-and-maps/ |title=The iPhone's M7 Motion coprocessor and Maps |publisher=TUAW |date=2013-09-12 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Colon |first=Alex |url=http://gigaom.com/2013/09/12/apples-m7-coprocessor-might-bring-big-improvements-to-its-mapping-abilities/ |title=Apple's M7 coprocessor might bring big improvements to its mapping abilities |publisher=GigaOM |date=2013-09-12 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Burns |first=Chris |url=http://www.slashgear.com/iphone-5s-apple-m7-coprocessor-knows-when-you-are-sleeping-12297615/ |title=iPhone 5S Apple M7 coprocessor \"knows\" when you are sleeping |publisher=SlashGear |date=2013-09-12 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref> Another application could be the ability to do indoor tracking and mapping.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gurman |first=Mark |url=http://9to5mac.com/2013/09/12/iphones-m7-motion-processor-to-integrate-with-maps-as-apple-develops-indoor-mapping-public-transit/ |title=iPhone's M7 motion processor to integrate with Maps as Apple develops indoor mapping, public transit |publisher=9to5Mac |date=2013-09-12 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref> In [[iOS 10]], the motion coprocessor is used to implement raise-to-wake functionality, reducing idle energy usage.\n\n== Products ==\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Coprocessor\n! iPhone\n! iPad\n! Other\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A7]], LPC18A1\n| [[iPhone 5S]]\n| [[iPad Air]]<br/>[[iPad mini 2]]<br/>[[iPad mini 3]]\n| (none)\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A8]]<br/>[[Apple A8X]]\n| [[iPhone 6]]<ref name=\"ifixiph6p\"/><br/>[[iPhone 6 Plus]]<ref name=\"ifixiph6\"/>\n| [[iPad Air 2]]<br/>[[iPad Mini 4]]\n| [[iPod Touch (6th generation)]]\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A9]]<br/>[[Apple A9X]]\n| [[iPhone 6S]]<br/>[[iPhone 6S Plus]]<br/>[[iPhone SE]]\n| [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 9.7\"]]<br/>[[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 12.9\"]]<br/>[[iPad (2017)|iPad (5th generation)]]\n| (none)\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A10 Fusion]]<br/>[[Apple A10X Fusion]]\n| [[iPhone 7]]<br/>[[iPhone 7 Plus]]\n| [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 10.5\"]]<br/>[[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 12.9\" (2nd generation)]]<br/>[[iPad (2018)|iPad (6th generation)]]\n| [[Apple TV 4K]]<br/>[[iPod Touch (7th generation)]]\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A11 Bionic]]\n| [[iPhone 8]]<br/>[[iPhone 8 Plus]]<br/>[[iPhone X]]\n| (none)\n| (none)\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A12|Apple A12 Bionic]]<br/>[[Apple A12X Bionic]]\n| [[iPhone XS]]<br/>[[iPhone XS Max]]<br/>[[iPhone XR]]\n| [[iPad Pro 11\"]]<br/>[[iPad Pro 12.9 3G\"|iPad Pro 12.9\" (3rd generation)]]<br/>[[iPad Air (2019)|iPad Air (3rd generation)]]<br/>[[iPad mini (5th generation)]]\n| (none)\n\n|}\n<ref>https://www.apple.com/ipad-pro/specs/</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:NXP LPC18A1.jpg|The LPC18A1, also known as the Apple M7. Manufactured week 29 in 2013.\nFile:LPC18A1-and-A7.jpg|The size difference between the A7 and the smaller LPC18A1\nFile:NXP LPC18B1.jpg|The LPC18B1, also known as the Apple M8. Manufactured week 28 in 2014.\nFile:LPC18B1-and-A8.jpg|The size difference between the A8 and the smaller LPC18B1\nFile:Apple A9 APL1022.jpg|The Apple A9 which has the on-die M9 coprocessor\nFile:Apple A9X.jpg|The Apple A9X which has the on-die M9 coprocessor\nFile:Apple A10 Fusion APL1W24.jpg|Apple A10 Fusion with on-die M10 coprocessor\nFile:Apple A10X Fusion.jpg|Apple A10X with on-die M10 motion co-processor\nFile:Apple A11.jpg|Apple A11 Bionic with on-die M11 motion co-processor\nFile:Apple A12.jpg|Apple A12 Bionic with on-die M12 motion co-processor\nFile:Apple A12X.jpg|Apple A12X Bionic with on-die M12 motion co-processor\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Apple mobile application processors]]\n* [[Apple A7]]\n* [[Apple A8]]\n* [[Apple A8X]]\n* [[Apple A9]]\n* [[Apple A9X]]\n* [[Apple A10 Fusion]]\n* [[Apple A10X Fusion]]\n* [[Apple A11 Bionic]]\n* [[Apple A12 Bionic]]\n* [[Apple A12X Bionic]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}{{Apple Inc. hardware}}{{Apple Inc.}}\n\n[[Category:Apple Inc. mobile processors|Motion coprocessors]]\n[[Category:Coprocessors]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox CPU\n| name           = Apple M-series coprocessors\n| image          = [[File:NXP LPC18A1.jpg|200px]]\n| caption        = The NXP LPC18A1, also known as the M7 motion coprocessor\n| produced-start = September 2013\n| produced-end   = present\n| slowest        = 150<ref name=\"NXP-docs\" >{{cite techreport |url=http://www.nxp.com/documents/leaflet/lpc18xx.pdf |title=NXP 150 MHz, 32-bit Cortex-M3 microcontrollers LPC1800 |number=9397 750 17002 |publisher=NXP Semiconductors |format=PDF |date=September 2010 |accessdate=September 20, 2013}}</ref> | slow-unit = MHz\n| size-from      = 90&nbsp;nm<ref name=\"NXP-docs\"/>\n| arch           = [[ARMv7-M]]<ref name=\"NXP-docs\"/>\n| microarch      = [[Cortex-M3]]<ref name=\"NXP-docs\"/>\n| code           = M7: LPC18A1<ref name=\"Chipworks-M7\" /><br />M8: LPC18B1<ref name=\"ifixiph6p\"/>\n| numcores       = 1<ref name=\"NXP-docs\"/>\n| manuf1         = [[NXP Semiconductors]]<ref name=\"Chipworks-M7\" /><br/>[[TSMC]] (under contract)<br>[[Samsung]] (under contract)<br/>[[Apple Inc.]] (licensee)\n| designfirm     = [[NXP Semiconductors]]\n}}\nThe '''Apple M-series coprocessors''' are motion [[coprocessor]]s used by [[Apple Inc.]] in their mobile devices. First released in 2013, their function is to collect sensor data from integrated [[accelerometer]]s, [[gyroscope]]s and [[compass]]es and offload the collecting and processing of sensor data from the main [[central processing unit]] (CPU).\n\n{{As of|2017|05}}, the M-series coprocessors so far released have been the '''M7''' (codename ''Oscar''), the '''M8''', the '''M9''', the '''M10''', the '''M11,''' the '''M12,''' and the '''M13'''. The M7 was introduced in September 2013 with the [[iPhone 5S]]<ref>{{cite web|last=Estes |first=Adam Clark |url=https://gizmodo.com/how-apples-m7-chip-makes-the-iphone-5s-the-ultimate-tr-1286594287 |title=How Apple's M7 Chip Makes the iPhone 5S the Ultimate Tracking Device |publisher=Gizmodo |date=2013-09-10 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sumra |first=Husain |url=http://www.macrumors.com/2013/09/10/iphone-5s-includes-new-m7-motion-coprocessor-for-health-and-fitness-tracking/ |title=iPhone 5s Includes New 'M7' Motion Coprocessor for Health and Fitness Tracking |publisher=MacRumors |date=2013-09-10 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref> and the updated version, M8 was introduced in September 2014 with the [[iPhone 6]] and also processes data from the [[barometer]] that is included in the [[iPhone 6]] and [[iPad Air 2]].<ref name=\"iphone6-tech\">[https://www.apple.com/iphone-6/technology/ Apple - iPhone 6 - Technology]</ref><ref name=\"ipadair2-tech\">[https://www.apple.com/ipad-air-2/performance/ Apple - iPad Air 2 - Performance]</ref> September 2015 brought the M9 motion coprocessor embedded within the [[Apple A9|A9]] chip found in the [[iPhone 6S]], [[iPhone 6S Plus]], [[iPhone SE]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-se/specs/|title=iPhone SE - Technical Specifications|website=Apple|access-date=2016-06-14}}</ref> and within the [[Apple A9X|A9X]] chip found in the [[iPad Pro]].<ref name=\"iPhone_6S_press_release\">[https://www.apple.com/pr/library/2015/09/09Apple-Introduces-iPhone-6s-iPhone-6s-Plus.html Apple Introduces iPhone 6s & iPhone 6s Plus]</ref><ref name=\"ipadpro_tech_specs\">[https://www.apple.com/ipad-pro/specs/ iPad Pro - Apple]</ref> The [[iPhone 7]], [[iPad Pro]] 10.5-inch and 12.9-inch feature the M10 motion coprocessor.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-7/specs/|title=iPhone 7 - Technical Specifications|website=Apple|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-08}}</ref>  Apple included the M11 in the [[iPhone 8]], 8 Plus and [[iPhone X]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-x/specs/|title=iPhone X - Technical Specifications|website=Apple|language=en-US|access-date=2017-09-17}}</ref>. The most recent addition to the M-series processor line is the M13, which first appeared embedded into the A13 Bionic processor found in the iPhone 11, 11 Pro and 11 Pro Max.\n\nChipworks found that the M7 most likely is a [[NXP Semiconductors|NXP]] [[LPC1800]] based [[microcontroller]] called '''LPC18A1'''. It uses an [[ARM Cortex-M#Cortex-M3|ARM Cortex-M3]] core with a customised packaging and naming scheme indicating that it is for an Apple customized part.<ref name=\"Chipworks-M7\">{{cite web|url=http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-iphone-5s/|title=Inside the iPhone 5s|first1=Jason|last1=Tanner|first2=Jim|last2=Morrison|first3=Dick|last3=James|first4=Ray|last4=Fontaine|first5=Phil|last5=Gamache|publisher=Chipworks|date=September 20, 2013|accessdate=September 20, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140803201521/http://www.chipworks.com/en/technical-competitive-analysis/resources/blog/inside-the-iphone-5s/|archive-date=August 3, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> [[iFixit]] have identified the\nM8 in the iPhone 6 to be an NXP device with a very similar name, the '''LPC18B1'''.<ref name=\"ifixiph6p\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/iPhone+6+Plus+Teardown/29206|publisher=iFixit|title=iPhone 6 Plus Teardown|accessdate=2014-09-20}}</ref><ref name=\"ifixiph6\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ifixit.com/Teardown/iPhone+6+Teardown/29213|publisher=iFixit|title=iPhone 6 Teardown|accessdate=2014-09-20}}</ref>\n\n== Usage ==\nThe Apple M7, M8, M9, M10, M11, M12 and M13 coprocessors collect, process, and store sensor data even if the device is asleep, and applications can retrieve data when the device is powered up again. This reduces power draw of the device and saves battery life.<ref name=\"AnandTech-iPhone5s-M7\">{{cite web |first=Anand |last=Lal Shimpi |url=http://anandtech.com/show/7335/the-iphone-5s-review/8 |title=The iPhone 5s Review: M7 Motion Coprocessor |publisher=AnandTech |date= 2013-09-17 |accessdate= 2013-09-18}}</ref> In addition to servicing the [[accelerometer]], [[gyroscope]], [[compass]], and in M8 and later coprocessors, [[barometer]], the M9 coprocessor can recognize [[Siri]] voice commands from the built in [[Microphone|microphones]] of the device.<ref name=\"Apple iPhone 6S Tech\">{{cite web |url=https://www.apple.com/iphone-6s/technology/ |title=iPhone 6s - Technology |publisher=[[Apple Inc.|Apple]] |date=September 8, 2015 |accessdate=September 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe M-series motion coprocessors are accessible to applications through the ''Core Motion'' [[Application programming interface|API]] introduced in [[iOS 7]], so they do, for example, allow [[fitness app]]s that track physical activity and access data from the M processors without constantly engaging the main application processor. They enable applications to be aware of what type of movement the user is experiencing, such as driving, walking, running, or sleeping.<ref>{{cite web|last=Martin |first=Mel |url=http://www.tuaw.com/2013/09/12/the-iphones-m7-motion-coprocessor-and-maps/ |title=The iPhone's M7 Motion coprocessor and Maps |publisher=TUAW |date=2013-09-12 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Colon |first=Alex |url=http://gigaom.com/2013/09/12/apples-m7-coprocessor-might-bring-big-improvements-to-its-mapping-abilities/ |title=Apple's M7 coprocessor might bring big improvements to its mapping abilities |publisher=GigaOM |date=2013-09-12 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Burns |first=Chris |url=http://www.slashgear.com/iphone-5s-apple-m7-coprocessor-knows-when-you-are-sleeping-12297615/ |title=iPhone 5S Apple M7 coprocessor \"knows\" when you are sleeping |publisher=SlashGear |date=2013-09-12 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref> Another application could be the ability to do indoor tracking and mapping.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gurman |first=Mark |url=http://9to5mac.com/2013/09/12/iphones-m7-motion-processor-to-integrate-with-maps-as-apple-develops-indoor-mapping-public-transit/ |title=iPhone's M7 motion processor to integrate with Maps as Apple develops indoor mapping, public transit |publisher=9to5Mac |date=2013-09-12 |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref> In [[iOS 10]], the motion coprocessor is used to implement raise-to-wake functionality, reducing idle energy usage.\n\n== Products ==\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n! Coprocessor\n! iPhone\n! iPad\n! Other\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A7]], LPC18A1\n| [[iPhone 5S]]\n| [[iPad Air]]<br/>[[iPad mini 2]]<br/>[[iPad mini 3]]\n| (none)\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A8]]<br/>[[Apple A8X]]\n| [[iPhone 6]]<ref name=\"ifixiph6p\"/><br/>[[iPhone 6 Plus]]<ref name=\"ifixiph6\"/>\n| [[iPad Air 2]]<br/>[[iPad Mini 4]]\n| [[iPod Touch (6th generation)]]\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A9]]<br/>[[Apple A9X]]\n| [[iPhone 6S]]<br/>[[iPhone 6S Plus]]<br/>[[iPhone SE]]\n| [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 9.7\"]]<br/>[[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 12.9\"]]<br/>[[iPad (2017)|iPad (5th generation)]]\n| (none)\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A10 Fusion]]<br/>[[Apple A10X Fusion]]\n| [[iPhone 7]]<br/>[[iPhone 7 Plus]]\n| [[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 10.5\"]]<br/>[[iPad Pro|iPad Pro 12.9\" (2nd generation)]]<br/>[[iPad (2018)|iPad (6th generation)]]\n| [[Apple TV 4K]]<br/>[[iPod Touch (7th generation)]]\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A11 Bionic]]\n| [[iPhone 8]]<br/>[[iPhone 8 Plus]]<br/>[[iPhone X]]\n| (none)\n| (none)\n\n|-\n! [[Apple A12|Apple A12 Bionic]]<br/>[[Apple A12X Bionic]]\n| [[iPhone XS]]<br/>[[iPhone XS Max]]<br/>[[iPhone XR]]\n| [[iPad Pro 11\"]]<br/>[[iPad Pro 12.9 3G\"|iPad Pro 12.9\" (3rd generation)]]<br/>[[iPad Air (2019)|iPad Air (3rd generation)]]<br/>[[iPad mini (5th generation)]]\n| (none)\n\n|}\n<ref>https://www.apple.com/ipad-pro/specs/</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:NXP LPC18A1.jpg|The LPC18A1, also known as the Apple M7. Manufactured week 29 in 2013.\nFile:LPC18A1-and-A7.jpg|The size difference between the A7 and the smaller LPC18A1\nFile:NXP LPC18B1.jpg|The LPC18B1, also known as the Apple M8. Manufactured week 28 in 2014.\nFile:LPC18B1-and-A8.jpg|The size difference between the A8 and the smaller LPC18B1\nFile:Apple A9 APL1022.jpg|The Apple A9 which has the on-die M9 coprocessor\nFile:Apple A9X.jpg|The Apple A9X which has the on-die M9 coprocessor\nFile:Apple A10 Fusion APL1W24.jpg|Apple A10 Fusion with on-die M10 coprocessor\nFile:Apple A10X Fusion.jpg|Apple A10X with on-die M10 motion co-processor\nFile:Apple A11.jpg|Apple A11 Bionic with on-die M11 motion co-processor\nFile:Apple A12.jpg|Apple A12 Bionic with on-die M12 motion co-processor\nFile:Apple A12X.jpg|Apple A12X Bionic with on-die M12 motion co-processor\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Apple mobile application processors]]\n* [[Apple A7]]\n* [[Apple A8]]\n* [[Apple A8X]]\n* [[Apple A9]]\n* [[Apple A9X]]\n* [[Apple A10 Fusion]]\n* [[Apple A10X Fusion]]\n* [[Apple A11 Bionic]]\n* [[Apple A12 Bionic]]\n* [[Apple A12X Bionic]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}{{Apple Inc. hardware}}{{Apple Inc.}}\n\n[[Category:Apple Inc. mobile processors|Motion coprocessors]]\n[[Category:Coprocessors]]\n[[Category:Products introduced in 2013]]\n", "name_user": "WILLLOWTHER", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.o